-- Sub-Saharan Africa Stocks: Dangote, Diamond Trust, Skye Bank
-- B y   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 2012-05-04T15:58:44Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-05-04/sub-saharan-africa-stocks-diamond-trust-bank-skye-bank-move.html
Kenya’s  All-Share Index (NSEASI)  gained for a
second day, adding 0.5 percent to 63.12 by the close in Nairobi.  The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index (NGSEINDX)  added 0.6
percent to 22,665.99 in Lagos, a third day of gains, according
to data compiled by Bloomberg. Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index (SEMDEX)  declined
less than 0.1 percent to 1,798.07 by the close in Port Louis.
The  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  declined 1.3 percent to 899.86 in
Windhoek.  The following shares were active in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Dangote Flour Mills Plc (DANGFLOU)   rose to the highest
in more than a month on speculation South Africa’s Tiger Brands
Ltd. plans to buy a stake in the Nigerian producer. The stock
jumped 4.9 percent to 4.74 naira.  Diamond Trust Bank of Kenya Ltd.  (DTKL KN), the East
African nation’s sixth-biggest lender, fell for a second day
after shareholders approved a plan to sell 24.5 million new
shares to existing stockholders. The stock slipped 1.5 percent
to 97.5 shillings.  Safaricom Ltd. (SAFCOM)  , Kenya’s biggest mobile-phone
company, rose to the highest in almost nine months on bets it
will announce stronger second-half profit next week. The stock
advanced 1.5 percent to 3.45 shillings.  Skye Bank Plc (SKYEBANK)   climbed the most in more than
three years, adding 8.1 percent to 4 naira. Profit after tax for
the three months through March rose to 3.48 billion naira (422.1
million) from 3.4 billion naira a year earlier, the Lagos-based
lender said on its website after the market closed yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
